WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.130 --> 00:00:08.963
- Be honest.

00:00:08.963 --> 00:00:10.080
Do you still get excited when you hear

00:00:10.080 --> 00:00:11.190
the Window startup sound?

00:00:15.900 --> 00:00:17.910
- It reminds me of a magic time.

00:00:17.910 --> 00:00:21.120
This feels like you know,
without it, there is no day

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:22.800
that you could start

00:00:22.800 --> 00:00:26.490
- Microsoft: an indispensable
and inescapable force

00:00:26.490 --> 00:00:30.030
for 50 years. The company
invented the software industry

00:00:30.030 --> 00:00:31.950
and changed the world as we know it.

00:00:31.950 --> 00:00:33.499
Transforming personal computing

00:00:33.499 --> 00:00:35.290
from a nerdy curiosity into

00:00:35.290 --> 00:00:37.350
a global necessity.

00:00:37.350 --> 00:00:38.510
- I'll cheat a little bit.

00:00:41.100 --> 00:00:43.560
With three CEOs spanning five decades,

00:00:43.560 --> 00:00:45.660
each leader marked a distinct chapter in

00:00:45.660 --> 00:00:47.190
technological history.

00:00:47.190 --> 00:00:49.020
- The thing they all
have in common is this

00:00:49.020 --> 00:00:50.790
extraordinary curiosity.

00:00:50.790 --> 00:00:52.680
You know, Bill is more of a reader.

00:00:52.680 --> 00:00:57.480
Steve studies numbers, finds
patterns and pictures in them

00:00:57.480 --> 00:00:59.940
and loves talking with people.

00:00:59.940 --> 00:01:03.360
Satya's like the Renaissance man CEO,

00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:05.820
- The software giant, has
lasted this long by catching

00:01:05.820 --> 00:01:09.060
and capitalizing on technology
waves constantly hedging

00:01:09.060 --> 00:01:11.430
their bets over an uncertain future.

00:01:11.430 --> 00:01:13.860
- We're always thinking about,
okay, what happens tomorrow?

00:01:13.860 --> 00:01:17.400
What's gonna happen tomorrow?
Will the company keep going?

00:01:17.400 --> 00:01:18.660
- They didn't catch them all,

00:01:18.660 --> 00:01:20.730
but just enough to stay relevant today.

00:01:22.350 --> 00:01:23.910
- There have been so many twists

00:01:23.910 --> 00:01:27.870
and turns in the technological
road. When I was in charge,

00:01:27.870 --> 00:01:29.820
you know, I'd sit up
all night thinking, oh,

00:01:29.820 --> 00:01:31.335
we're gonna miss this,
we're gonna miss that.

00:01:31.335 --> 00:01:32.501
The fact that we've been able to

00:01:32.501 --> 00:01:35.134
navigate this changing environment,

00:01:35.134 --> 00:01:38.370
kind of a miracle to me,
you know, here we are now,

00:01:38.370 --> 00:01:40.440
you know, the road's
got all these AI twists

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:42.990
and turns that taught
you with a little bit

00:01:42.990 --> 00:01:44.010
of advice from Steve

00:01:44.010 --> 00:01:48.810
and I gets to to drive the
the car around these curves.

00:01:48.810 --> 00:01:50.940
- Microsoft loomed large for years,

00:01:50.940 --> 00:01:53.190
but as the land of tech
giants got more crowded

00:01:53.190 --> 00:01:54.720
and more competitive, it seemed

00:01:54.720 --> 00:01:58.200
to drift into the corporate
doldrums until Satya Nadella

00:01:58.200 --> 00:02:00.420
and a big bet on OpenAI brought them

00:02:00.420 --> 00:02:01.590
back into the zeitgeist.

00:02:02.550 --> 00:02:04.560
But the next generation of Microsoft has

00:02:04.560 --> 00:02:08.160
to do more than rely on
ChatGPT's strategic advantage.

00:02:08.160 --> 00:02:09.960
- We're at a really pivotal moment here.

00:02:09.960 --> 00:02:11.610
The company still needs

00:02:11.610 --> 00:02:14.310
to figure out a consumer centric vision,

00:02:14.310 --> 00:02:18.720
a consumer-first vision, but
it's not in Microsoft's DNA

00:02:18.720 --> 00:02:21.600
and it remains to be
seen if they can do it.

00:02:35.130 --> 00:02:37.710
- Welcome to Microsoft's 50th birthday.

00:02:37.710 --> 00:02:40.470
We're gonna go inside
to watch the main event.

00:02:40.470 --> 00:02:41.760
- Are we on The Circuit?

00:02:41.760 --> 00:02:42.593
- You're on The Circuit.

00:02:42.593 --> 00:02:43.426
- Right now?

00:02:43.426 --> 00:02:44.259
- You're on The Circuit.

00:02:44.259 --> 00:02:45.652
- Just a cameo from the competition.

00:02:45.652 --> 00:02:46.485
- Oh My God.

00:02:46.485 --> 00:02:47.318
- I'll open the door for you.

00:02:47.318 --> 00:02:48.351
- I love The Circuit!

00:02:48.351 --> 00:02:49.184
Thank you.

00:02:53.970 --> 00:02:58.260
- Welcome to the era of AI
Companions and of co-pilots.

00:02:58.260 --> 00:03:01.120
It starts with Bill and Steve who are both

00:03:01.120 --> 00:03:02.380
here with us today.

00:03:06.700 --> 00:03:08.620
- Hi. We're waiting for Bill.

00:03:09.850 --> 00:03:14.517
He's finishing up an interview
and then he's coming here.

00:03:16.870 --> 00:03:20.440
- Okay, Bill, happy birthday.
- Thank you.

00:03:20.440 --> 00:03:23.440
- 50 years. So it's 1975.

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:25.390
What's going on inside Bill's brain?

00:03:25.390 --> 00:03:27.610
Did you and Paul think
you had something this

00:03:27.610 --> 00:03:29.410
big in your hands?

00:03:29.410 --> 00:03:32.590
- Well, we knew that
software would be important.

00:03:32.590 --> 00:03:35.365
You know, we said when
people thought it was crazy,

00:03:35.365 --> 00:03:38.410
a computer on every
desk and in every home.

00:03:38.410 --> 00:03:41.050
And so we saw it as this
tool of empowerment.

00:03:41.050 --> 00:03:42.310
- Microsoft's journey begins

00:03:42.310 --> 00:03:45.280
with these two young hackers
in the Pacific Northwest,

00:03:45.280 --> 00:03:47.380
Bill Gates and Paul Allen.

00:03:47.380 --> 00:03:50.230
They started obsessing over
the emerging computer industry

00:03:50.230 --> 00:03:53.650
after spotting this cover
of Popular Electronics.

00:03:53.650 --> 00:03:56.050
It's rudimentary stuff
by today's standards,

00:03:56.050 --> 00:03:58.030
a mini computer kit that you'd program

00:03:58.030 --> 00:04:00.040
by punching holes into paper.

00:04:00.040 --> 00:04:01.450
Gates and Alan were hooked

00:04:01.450 --> 00:04:04.120
and developed a new
programming language for it.

00:04:04.120 --> 00:04:07.180
That became the foundational
software for Microsoft.

00:04:07.180 --> 00:04:11.080
- People probably remember
the Apple II, the TRS-80,

00:04:11.080 --> 00:04:14.770
the Commodore PET, those
were the first computers

00:04:14.770 --> 00:04:17.050
that sold literally in the millions,

00:04:17.050 --> 00:04:19.600
and all of them included Microsoft Basics.

00:04:19.600 --> 00:04:22.300
So the reason you could write
a program, try things out was

00:04:22.300 --> 00:04:25.720
because we'd worked with
each of those companies.

00:04:25.720 --> 00:04:28.360
Then the IBM PC comes along,

00:04:28.360 --> 00:04:30.580
- IBM now had 50% market share

00:04:30.580 --> 00:04:33.160
and was defining what a PC meant.

00:04:33.160 --> 00:04:36.550
- Gates and Allen got their
software on the first IBM PCs

00:04:36.550 --> 00:04:38.470
and in a stroke of business genius inked,

00:04:38.470 --> 00:04:40.750
a non-exclusive deal, making it possible

00:04:40.750 --> 00:04:43.870
for other manufacturers
like Apple to license it.

00:04:43.870 --> 00:04:45.880
What was the scariest this-might-not-work

00:04:45.880 --> 00:04:47.650
moment along the way?

00:04:47.650 --> 00:04:51.280
- Well, there were times in
our relationship with IBM

00:04:51.280 --> 00:04:54.130
that were very complicated.

00:04:54.130 --> 00:04:56.920
Very early on in the
history of the company,

00:04:56.920 --> 00:04:58.570
we had a dispute with our customer.

00:04:58.570 --> 00:05:00.370
They weren't paying us. Thereafter,

00:05:00.370 --> 00:05:02.650
I said, I'm gonna have
enough money in the bank

00:05:02.650 --> 00:05:04.210
to pay everyone's salary for a year,

00:05:04.210 --> 00:05:05.800
even if nobody pays me anything.

00:05:05.800 --> 00:05:08.410
So I was very conservative financially

00:05:08.410 --> 00:05:12.670
and we were always worried
that once somebody realized

00:05:12.670 --> 00:05:17.050
what we realized, that
they might, you know,

00:05:17.050 --> 00:05:18.340
do a good job as well.

00:05:18.340 --> 00:05:20.080
So, you know, why didn't IBM

00:05:20.080 --> 00:05:22.480
who had all the capital in the world

00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:25.120
and great people, why
couldn't they do what we did?

00:05:25.120 --> 00:05:27.640
And we thought, well, we're
more dedicated to software.

00:05:27.640 --> 00:05:30.040
We're gonna price this
stuff super, super low

00:05:30.040 --> 00:05:32.230
and make it available to everyone.

00:05:32.230 --> 00:05:36.800
Welcome to the Microsoft
MS-DOS 5 upgrade training

00:05:36.800 --> 00:05:37.730
It's...

00:05:39.465 --> 00:05:40.298
New!

00:05:40.298 --> 00:05:42.889
- Productivity software
was the hot new thing,

00:05:42.889 --> 00:05:44.470
transforming the workforce

00:05:44.470 --> 00:05:46.750
and Microsoft soon became
the company to work for

00:05:46.750 --> 00:05:49.240
attracting people like this guy.

00:05:50.380 --> 00:05:53.385
This is a classic throwback video.

00:05:53.385 --> 00:05:55.925
- Yeah, I know.

00:05:55.925 --> 00:05:57.491
My daughter makes a lot of fun

00:05:57.491 --> 00:05:58.887
of my accent even here.

00:05:58.887 --> 00:05:59.720
As you can see,

00:05:59.720 --> 00:06:01.528
the most important architectural

00:06:01.528 --> 00:06:02.786
requirement for this piece...

00:06:02.786 --> 00:06:04.730
- So you're a technical
product manager here,

00:06:04.730 --> 00:06:06.590
you're demoing Excel.

00:06:06.590 --> 00:06:09.410
Who's that guy? Like what's
he thinking at that time?

00:06:09.410 --> 00:06:11.360
- It was an Excel demo with a,

00:06:11.360 --> 00:06:14.480
I think a DB2 connector back to at

00:06:14.480 --> 00:06:17.150
that time a mini computer

00:06:17.150 --> 00:06:19.430
and it was the beginning
of that client server era.

00:06:19.430 --> 00:06:20.630
- Did that guy have any idea

00:06:20.630 --> 00:06:21.845
he'd be running the place one day?

00:06:21.845 --> 00:06:24.980
- No chance. I was like
hoping to stay there in my job

00:06:24.980 --> 00:06:26.900
for the next month if I could.

00:06:26.900 --> 00:06:29.180
I was lucky enough to get hired.

00:06:29.180 --> 00:06:32.990
I never felt any job I was
doing at Microsoft somehow was a

00:06:32.990 --> 00:06:34.610
path to the next job.

00:06:34.610 --> 00:06:37.160
The job I was doing was
like the most exciting thing

00:06:37.160 --> 00:06:39.680
that I could be doing
and I gave it it all and

00:06:39.680 --> 00:06:41.570
and the rest is history.

00:06:41.570 --> 00:06:44.960
- Nadella joined Microsoft in
1992 when the company started

00:06:44.960 --> 00:06:46.010
to cement its position

00:06:46.010 --> 00:06:48.950
as the default operating
system for the world.

00:06:48.950 --> 00:06:52.580
- Really like the origin
of Microsoft was this idea

00:06:52.580 --> 00:06:55.490
that you could make money
off of selling software.

00:06:55.490 --> 00:06:57.560
Before that, everybody sold the hardware

00:06:57.560 --> 00:06:58.760
and you got software with it,

00:06:58.760 --> 00:07:01.040
but it was the idea that you
could have a software company

00:07:01.040 --> 00:07:02.870
and that was really revolutionary.

00:07:02.870 --> 00:07:05.150
- Dina Bass is a Bloomberg
tech reporter who's covered

00:07:05.150 --> 00:07:07.550
Microsoft since 1999.

00:07:07.550 --> 00:07:10.430
That's 25 years of war stories.

00:07:10.430 --> 00:07:12.470
- There have been so
many like ebbs and flows

00:07:12.470 --> 00:07:13.940
and waves and this and that.

00:07:13.940 --> 00:07:17.270
Some of it is routine where,
you know, oh, another version

00:07:17.270 --> 00:07:21.500
of Windows and some of it is
a 4:30 AM phone call on your

00:07:21.500 --> 00:07:25.520
home phone with Microsoft PR
talking into your voicemail

00:07:25.520 --> 00:07:27.230
about the fact that they're about

00:07:27.230 --> 00:07:30.260
to launch a hostile takeover bid for Yahoo

00:07:30.260 --> 00:07:32.540
and you are seven months pregnant

00:07:32.540 --> 00:07:34.098
and you're like, "Nah."

00:07:34.098 --> 00:07:35.810
Nah, nah.

00:07:35.810 --> 00:07:38.600
When I moved to Seattle, it
was really a different place.

00:07:38.600 --> 00:07:40.100
It was the late nineties

00:07:40.100 --> 00:07:41.960
and there was just this
whole culture of the,

00:07:41.960 --> 00:07:44.390
the stock had gone crazy in that decade.

00:07:46.250 --> 00:07:47.300
So there was this whole culture

00:07:47.300 --> 00:07:48.728
of Microsoft millionaires. Tech

00:07:48.728 --> 00:07:51.230
- Tech employees are a unique breed.

00:07:51.230 --> 00:07:53.272
Do they still call them
Microsofties?

00:07:53.272 --> 00:07:54.105
I think so.

00:07:54.105 --> 00:07:56.179
I mean, at least we progressed
from Microserfs, right?

00:07:57.050 --> 00:07:59.780
Microsoft nearly dominated the PC market,

00:07:59.780 --> 00:08:02.150
practically printing money
by selling new versions

00:08:02.150 --> 00:08:03.380
of Windows and office.

00:08:04.490 --> 00:08:06.290
But shipping software back then had an

00:08:06.290 --> 00:08:07.460
entirely different meaning.

00:08:09.110 --> 00:08:11.630
- When the company would
finish work on a product,

00:08:11.630 --> 00:08:13.970
it was called RTM,
release to manufacturing.

00:08:13.970 --> 00:08:15.710
That was when you froze the code

00:08:15.710 --> 00:08:18.560
and you sent it off to the nice
people that published discs,

00:08:18.560 --> 00:08:21.050
which for your younger
viewers is a circular thing

00:08:21.050 --> 00:08:22.490
that you put in a computer.

00:08:22.490 --> 00:08:24.800
There'd be cascading
turns of people, you know,

00:08:24.800 --> 00:08:26.930
signing off on their own code,

00:08:26.930 --> 00:08:28.400
signing off that they were done.

00:08:28.400 --> 00:08:30.950
And at the end of it,
there was a giant party.

00:08:30.950 --> 00:08:32.840
People would end up in the fountains,

00:08:32.840 --> 00:08:35.420
people would end up getting
thrown into Lake Bill.

00:08:35.420 --> 00:08:37.122
We saw Steve Ballmer jumping into

00:08:37.122 --> 00:08:38.122
- Lake Bill.

00:08:44.450 --> 00:08:46.100
- I like to be excited.

00:08:46.100 --> 00:08:48.500
There was so much to be
excited about at Microsoft.

00:08:48.500 --> 00:08:49.910
We were doing great things

00:08:49.910 --> 00:08:54.020
and you know, trying to really,
if you will, be cheerleaders

00:08:54.020 --> 00:08:57.090
for a whole industry and
that was a lot of fun.

00:08:57.090 --> 00:08:59.550
- People brought Super Soakers to campus

00:08:59.550 --> 00:09:01.500
and there was a giant water fight.

00:09:01.500 --> 00:09:03.090
To basically to prepare for this,

00:09:03.090 --> 00:09:04.590
Microsoft, which has a very nice

00:09:04.590 --> 00:09:05.670
and pricey art collection,

00:09:05.670 --> 00:09:08.010
would take the art down from the walls

00:09:08.010 --> 00:09:09.810
because they didn't
want it to get damaged.

00:09:09.810 --> 00:09:13.170
But it was a young culture
that was kind of fun,

00:09:13.170 --> 00:09:14.203
which I think people don't

00:09:14.203 --> 00:09:15.630
really associate with Microsoft.

00:09:15.630 --> 00:09:17.490
- Microsoft reached a
pinnacle with the launch

00:09:17.490 --> 00:09:19.230
of Windows 95.

00:09:19.230 --> 00:09:21.120
It was a cultural moment.

00:09:21.120 --> 00:09:22.290
- We had Jay Leno

00:09:22.290 --> 00:09:23.520
and it was kind

00:09:23.520 --> 00:09:27.780
of maybe the time when people
realized Microsoft was quite a

00:09:27.780 --> 00:09:30.390
unique company. Office had come together,

00:09:30.390 --> 00:09:32.760
the graphics interface had
come together, you know,

00:09:32.760 --> 00:09:35.973
on all the different systems,
whether it was Apple Macintosh

00:09:35.973 --> 00:09:38.010
or Windows on the PC,

00:09:38.010 --> 00:09:40.200
we were providing the top application.

00:09:40.200 --> 00:09:44.370
So that was definitely a fun
day that, you know, showed

00:09:44.370 --> 00:09:46.590
that we had some special sauce.

00:09:47.430 --> 00:09:48.930
- People lined up around the block

00:09:48.930 --> 00:09:51.780
to get their hands on the
latest operating system, eager

00:09:51.780 --> 00:09:55.770
to explore ways to click type
and create with computers.

00:09:55.770 --> 00:09:59.310
Microsoft sold over 40 million
copies in its first year

00:09:59.310 --> 00:10:02.550
- And in that moment there's
also kind of the seeds

00:10:02.550 --> 00:10:04.020
of their kind of downfall

00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:06.360
because in Windows 95 they don't have

00:10:06.360 --> 00:10:07.500
anything internet-oriented.

00:10:07.500 --> 00:10:09.570
They don't realize it's gonna be a thing

00:10:09.570 --> 00:10:12.720
and all of a sudden you
see browsers come up,

00:10:12.720 --> 00:10:15.390
you see the internet
start to become important

00:10:15.390 --> 00:10:17.490
and they're completely flat-footed.

00:10:17.490 --> 00:10:19.500
So you have a few things
going on at once in that kind

00:10:19.500 --> 00:10:21.780
of canonical "evil empire" era.

00:10:22.620 --> 00:10:24.660
- This is when the company
started to get in trouble

00:10:24.660 --> 00:10:26.190
with the US government.

00:10:26.190 --> 00:10:29.100
Microsoft was accused of
wielding its market power,

00:10:29.100 --> 00:10:31.050
bundling its browser with Windows to try

00:10:31.050 --> 00:10:32.310
to ride the internet wave.

00:10:33.300 --> 00:10:36.060
They got big. Monopoly big, according

00:10:36.060 --> 00:10:37.350
to the Department of Justice.

00:10:38.370 --> 00:10:40.830
- How many of you use a PC without

00:10:40.830 --> 00:10:42.780
Microsoft's operating system?

00:10:44.130 --> 00:10:45.600
- Gentlemen, that's a monopoly.

00:10:45.600 --> 00:10:49.230
- You were criticized for your
aggressive business tactics

00:10:49.230 --> 00:10:50.760
and being anti-competitive.

00:10:50.760 --> 00:10:53.310
How do you reflect on that period?

00:10:53.310 --> 00:10:56.250
- Well, we were so successful

00:10:57.240 --> 00:11:00.090
and one of the great
rewards, if you're, you know,

00:11:00.090 --> 00:11:02.430
that successful is the government comes in

00:11:02.430 --> 00:11:05.370
and says, okay, you know,
do they have to do things

00:11:05.370 --> 00:11:06.900
to help out your competitors?

00:11:06.900 --> 00:11:08.700
Did you follow all those rules?

00:11:08.700 --> 00:11:11.340
So yes, at that same time

00:11:11.340 --> 00:11:15.540
as the internet era was
coming along in the

00:11:15.540 --> 00:11:19.350
90s, we were involved in a US

00:11:19.350 --> 00:11:21.000
government lawsuit.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.070
Then Brad Smith came along.

00:11:23.070 --> 00:11:26.190
- Microsoft President
Brad Smith joined in 1993

00:11:26.190 --> 00:11:28.140
as a budding technology lawyer.

00:11:28.140 --> 00:11:29.757
You can find him at places
like Davos,

00:11:29.757 --> 00:11:31.481
liaising with heads of state

00:11:31.481 --> 00:11:33.522
or at Microsoft's Treehouse.

00:11:35.190 --> 00:11:39.630
You helped navigate Microsoft
through one of maybe one

00:11:39.630 --> 00:11:42.030
of the most challenging
times in corporate history.

00:11:42.030 --> 00:11:44.550
Bill said the company could have died

00:11:44.550 --> 00:11:46.080
during the antitrust battle.

00:11:46.080 --> 00:11:48.330
What stands out to you from that time?

00:11:48.330 --> 00:11:52.200
- We needed to figure out
how to resolve disputes

00:11:52.200 --> 00:11:55.630
and not just figure what
it might take to win them.

00:11:55.630 --> 00:11:58.240
And that really meant making peace.

00:11:58.240 --> 00:12:00.370
And when I got the job

00:12:00.370 --> 00:12:04.780
of general counsel back in 2001
when I was selected, I said

00:12:04.780 --> 00:12:06.790
to Bill and Steve and others, look,

00:12:06.790 --> 00:12:08.440
if you wanna go make peace

00:12:08.440 --> 00:12:11.050
and negotiate agreements, I'm
probably the right person.

00:12:11.050 --> 00:12:12.280
And if you don't wanna do that,

00:12:12.280 --> 00:12:14.830
then I'm probably not the right person.

00:12:14.830 --> 00:12:17.200
because I had a strategy I believed in.

00:12:17.200 --> 00:12:19.900
- We were able to work a
settlement out with the government

00:12:19.900 --> 00:12:22.120
and you know, we've been
a lot more aware of, okay,

00:12:22.120 --> 00:12:24.970
let's constantly be in
touch with the governments

00:12:24.970 --> 00:12:26.830
around the world, make
sure they're good with

00:12:26.830 --> 00:12:28.330
what we're doing and that.

00:12:28.330 --> 00:12:30.700
And so we haven't had

00:12:30.700 --> 00:12:34.210
anything intense like we did
there in the late 90s.

00:12:34.210 --> 00:12:36.250
- The Microsoft antitrust
case has relevance

00:12:36.250 --> 00:12:38.410
for both Google and Meta today.

00:12:38.410 --> 00:12:40.870
Both companies are facing
down lawsuits in a bid

00:12:40.870 --> 00:12:43.687
to break up dominant tech
companies once again.

00:12:43.687 --> 00:12:45.430
That was sort of the beginning

00:12:45.430 --> 00:12:48.280
of a challenging time for
innovation at the company.

00:12:48.280 --> 00:12:49.480
Was it bad for Microsoft,

00:12:49.480 --> 00:12:51.970
but good for the industry in a way?

00:12:51.970 --> 00:12:55.360
- No company will ever
hit every wave better

00:12:55.360 --> 00:12:56.530
than everyone else.

00:12:56.530 --> 00:12:58.675
It just, that's not the
way the world works.

00:12:58.675 --> 00:13:01.840
Now, it is the case that
if you're distracted,

00:13:01.840 --> 00:13:04.360
you're much less likely
to hit the next wave.

00:13:04.360 --> 00:13:07.660
And I think it is always
worth remembering,

00:13:07.660 --> 00:13:08.950
it is a big world.

00:13:10.150 --> 00:13:13.150
If you don't hit a wave,
somebody else will.

00:13:13.150 --> 00:13:15.700
You have the opportunity
to get the next one.

00:13:15.700 --> 00:13:17.230
- Some people will blame

00:13:17.230 --> 00:13:19.660
that on the distraction
from the antitrust case.

00:13:19.660 --> 00:13:22.330
But some of it really was
just a failure to understand

00:13:22.330 --> 00:13:24.490
where the market was going, to understand

00:13:24.490 --> 00:13:28.270
what consumers wanted, what
office users wanted, right?

00:13:28.270 --> 00:13:30.770
- So they miss search,
they miss mobile.

00:13:30.770 --> 00:13:31.603
- Right.

00:13:31.603 --> 00:13:33.478
They miss social basically.

00:13:33.478 --> 00:13:36.261
And the stock is flat for years.

00:13:36.261 --> 00:13:37.720
This is the Steve Balmer era.

00:13:37.720 --> 00:13:39.820
- How much do you think this advanced

00:13:39.820 --> 00:13:41.440
operating environment is worth?

00:13:41.440 --> 00:13:43.450
- Employee number 30 at Microsoft.

00:13:43.450 --> 00:13:46.360
Steve Balmer is the energetic,
exuberant sales whiz

00:13:46.360 --> 00:13:49.570
who led Microsoft from 2000 to 2014.

00:13:49.570 --> 00:13:51.880
He put the big in Big Tech.

00:13:51.880 --> 00:13:54.250
- When it was Bill to Steve,
it was sort of obvious

00:13:54.250 --> 00:13:56.500
because Steve was the
president of the company.

00:13:56.500 --> 00:13:58.960
He had been Bill's co-pilot, if you will,

00:13:58.960 --> 00:14:01.300
for basically 20 years.

00:14:01.300 --> 00:14:04.990
- When it first stepped
in the role, I said, wow,

00:14:04.990 --> 00:14:07.060
this is actually quite different.

00:14:07.060 --> 00:14:08.830
I really understood what it means

00:14:08.830 --> 00:14:12.455
to be the in "the buck
stops here" position.

00:14:12.455 --> 00:14:15.135
- Developers! Developers!

00:14:15.135 --> 00:14:16.840
- Developers! Developers! Developers!

00:14:16.840 --> 00:14:19.420
It's part of my greatest hits I guess.

00:14:19.420 --> 00:14:21.520
And I'll never shake it.

00:14:21.520 --> 00:14:25.270
- Your 25th anniversary,
you jumped out of a cake.

00:14:25.270 --> 00:14:27.605
I want, I want a do over.

00:14:27.605 --> 00:14:29.470
- I don't, I didn't even remember that.

00:14:29.470 --> 00:14:32.770
- You know, I miss
Ballmer-style product launches.

00:14:32.770 --> 00:14:34.480
Do you think tech's too serious now?

00:14:34.480 --> 00:14:35.770
- I always thought,
okay, you're gonna have

00:14:35.770 --> 00:14:37.270
fewer characters.

00:14:37.270 --> 00:14:40.090
You know, Bill Gates, a
character larger-than-life.

00:14:40.090 --> 00:14:42.790
Larry Ellison, a character,
larger-than-life.

00:14:42.790 --> 00:14:44.500
Steve Jobs obviously.

00:14:44.500 --> 00:14:46.060
And yet I think there's
still some characters.

00:14:46.060 --> 00:14:47.290
The AI thing is tricky

00:14:47.290 --> 00:14:50.650
because if you don't seem
serious enough then people won't

00:14:50.650 --> 00:14:52.700
trust you with the privacy.

00:14:52.700 --> 00:14:56.600
You know, the the, the issues
that AI generates uniquely.

00:14:56.600 --> 00:14:59.780
So I see a little bit less
of the, "Hey! Let's do the...

00:14:59.780 --> 00:15:01.520
- Yeah, yeah,
- The big joker" thing.

00:15:01.520 --> 00:15:04.820
'cause it's just tougher
with these kinds of products.

00:15:04.820 --> 00:15:05.870
- During Ballmer's tenure,

00:15:05.870 --> 00:15:08.450
Microsoft wandered into
its wilderness years,

00:15:08.450 --> 00:15:10.670
battling fresh challenges
from Google and search

00:15:10.670 --> 00:15:11.780
and Apple and mobile.

00:15:12.620 --> 00:15:13.850
A new acronym emerged

00:15:13.850 --> 00:15:15.980
that described the big
tech stocks of the moment.

00:15:15.980 --> 00:15:17.570
And it didn't include Microsoft.

00:15:18.470 --> 00:15:20.900
the company just couldn't
connect with the shifting needs

00:15:20.900 --> 00:15:23.150
and tastes of consumers.

00:15:23.150 --> 00:15:26.360
The company missed mobile
and social and search.

00:15:26.360 --> 00:15:28.850
Do you ever look back and think, what if?

00:15:28.850 --> 00:15:30.800
- Not too much actually, you know,

00:15:30.800 --> 00:15:33.530
did the company miss search?

00:15:33.530 --> 00:15:37.670
No, because it, all the stuff,
including Satya, who worked on

00:15:37.670 --> 00:15:40.520
that stuff, all that
stuff is now fundamental

00:15:40.520 --> 00:15:42.260
to what's going on in AI.

00:15:42.260 --> 00:15:45.980
So yes, there was a cycle
of it the company missed.

00:15:45.980 --> 00:15:49.310
The one I would would
highlight is the intelligence

00:15:49.310 --> 00:15:52.520
that you carry with you, i.e. your phone.

00:15:52.520 --> 00:15:57.520
That's the one I say, ah, and
I know why I, we missed it.

00:15:57.560 --> 00:16:00.470
Missed meaning we don't
have a strong position,

00:16:00.470 --> 00:16:02.210
we have no position anymore.

00:16:02.210 --> 00:16:04.550
But I think that

00:16:04.550 --> 00:16:07.700
the company has really
thrived despite that.

00:16:07.700 --> 00:16:10.280
I'm proud of that. And
you know, are there things

00:16:10.280 --> 00:16:12.440
that Satya's missing right now?

00:16:12.440 --> 00:16:15.470
I'm sure you know, 15 years
from now he'll look back

00:16:15.470 --> 00:16:17.630
and say [expletive],
could have done that one.

00:16:17.630 --> 00:16:19.580
Sorry, oh shoot, could
have done that one better.

00:16:20.810 --> 00:16:22.490
But there you have it.

00:16:22.490 --> 00:16:24.650
- We ran a bunch of charts that tried

00:16:24.650 --> 00:16:26.330
to track his performance.

00:16:26.330 --> 00:16:27.470
If you looked at profit,

00:16:27.470 --> 00:16:29.660
if you looked at revenue, it went up.

00:16:29.660 --> 00:16:33.170
The chart that just
was down was the stock.

00:16:33.170 --> 00:16:34.280
And there was just,

00:16:34.280 --> 00:16:35.930
it seemed like there
was nothing they could

00:16:35.930 --> 00:16:37.040
do right at that point.

00:16:37.040 --> 00:16:39.320
And again, it's not totally accurate

00:16:39.320 --> 00:16:40.340
to say they missed mobile.

00:16:40.340 --> 00:16:42.050
They knew it was gonna be big,

00:16:42.050 --> 00:16:43.970
they couldn't figure
out what people wanted.

00:16:43.970 --> 00:16:46.580
Bill Gates loved the idea
of a tablet computer,

00:16:46.580 --> 00:16:49.070
a pen computer, he called
it in the 90s.

00:16:49.070 --> 00:16:51.380
- It's a tablet and there's a pen here.

00:16:51.380 --> 00:16:52.760
- He had wanted to do that forever

00:16:52.760 --> 00:16:56.090
and they finally released
one and in the early 00s

00:16:56.090 --> 00:16:58.730
and it's not something that anyone wants.

00:16:58.730 --> 00:17:01.640
And then Steve Jobs gets
up there with the iPad

00:17:01.640 --> 00:17:03.530
and it's exactly what
people are looking for.

00:17:03.530 --> 00:17:05.030
Now there's a couple of exceptions.

00:17:05.030 --> 00:17:07.520
In 2001, they released the Xbox,

00:17:09.050 --> 00:17:10.520
which remains the, you know,

00:17:10.520 --> 00:17:13.550
the biggest American gaming empire.

00:17:13.550 --> 00:17:15.680
It was a tough decision for them to make.

00:17:15.680 --> 00:17:18.500
Bill and Steve both were
unsure at various points.

00:17:18.500 --> 00:17:19.550
There was a lot of screaming

00:17:19.550 --> 00:17:21.544
and yelling around that decision.

00:17:21.544 --> 00:17:24.235
Bill, in a very foul-mouthed tirade

00:17:24.235 --> 00:17:26.110
at a meeting on Valentine's Day,

00:17:26.110 --> 00:17:28.160
accused the team working on it of,

00:17:28.160 --> 00:17:30.350
I'm not gonna use this
exact wording on television,

00:17:30.350 --> 00:17:33.890
but messing up everything he
had created at the company.

00:17:33.890 --> 00:17:36.530
Steve at this point is six weeks

00:17:36.530 --> 00:17:38.720
or so into his tenure as CEO,

00:17:38.720 --> 00:17:41.090
and this is the first major
decision he has to make.

00:17:41.090 --> 00:17:43.790
Am I going to green
light this Xbox or not?

00:17:43.790 --> 00:17:45.320
And he decides to go for it, but not

00:17:45.320 --> 00:17:47.750
before raking the team over the coals.

00:17:47.750 --> 00:17:49.770
That ended up being a
really prescient decision

00:17:49.770 --> 00:17:51.000
by Steve Ballmer though.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:53.670
The other thing that Steve
did that was really important,

00:17:53.670 --> 00:17:58.140
he decided to do some really
smart things in terms of cloud

00:17:58.140 --> 00:18:00.900
- Ballmer became the bridge
from Microsoft's PC era

00:18:00.900 --> 00:18:03.840
to its cloud future, a
transformation sparked

00:18:03.840 --> 00:18:04.920
by a competitive threat

00:18:04.920 --> 00:18:07.620
next door. Amazon identified

00:18:07.620 --> 00:18:10.200
that cloud computing would
be the next opportunity.

00:18:10.200 --> 00:18:12.390
So Ballmer put together
a team led by Satya

00:18:12.390 --> 00:18:13.860
Nadella to try to catch up

00:18:13.860 --> 00:18:15.510
and get a piece of the emerging market.

00:18:16.680 --> 00:18:18.480
Microsoft then launched Azure

00:18:18.480 --> 00:18:20.250
and brought office apps to the cloud.

00:18:21.120 --> 00:18:22.620
- It's a really pivotal moment

00:18:22.620 --> 00:18:26.940
because Microsoft at this point
has been surveying customers

00:18:26.940 --> 00:18:29.310
about whether they wanna move to the cloud

00:18:30.210 --> 00:18:33.210
and customers are telling
them we're not ready.

00:18:33.210 --> 00:18:38.070
And so the person that
preceded Satya in that division

00:18:38.070 --> 00:18:42.120
basically tells Steve Ballmer
customers don't want it,

00:18:42.120 --> 00:18:44.160
we shouldn't move this quickly.

00:18:44.160 --> 00:18:47.280
And Steve looks at that
executive, a guy named Bob Muglia

00:18:47.280 --> 00:18:49.950
and says, "Well then,
Bob, you're not my guy.

00:18:49.950 --> 00:18:52.080
And he replaces him with Satya.

00:18:52.080 --> 00:18:54.990
And there's like a
sliding doors moment where

00:18:54.990 --> 00:18:56.190
that doesn't happen.

00:18:56.190 --> 00:18:57.960
Satya never becomes CEO

00:18:57.960 --> 00:19:01.050
and you know, God only
knows where the company is.

00:19:01.050 --> 00:19:03.000
- I understand that that Bill spent a lot

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:05.850
of time succession planning
when he handed the reins to you

00:19:05.850 --> 00:19:08.250
and that you also spent a lot
of time succession planning.

00:19:08.250 --> 00:19:10.560
When you pass the reigns to Satya.

00:19:10.560 --> 00:19:12.870
What's the key to building a company

00:19:12.870 --> 00:19:15.030
that outlasts its founder?

00:19:15.030 --> 00:19:19.065
- It was super important to
let Satya have his space.

00:19:19.065 --> 00:19:21.450
- And I think that was a key learning.

00:19:21.450 --> 00:19:24.390
'cause when Bill and I, we
sort of had a long handoff,

00:19:24.390 --> 00:19:27.720
and so in a sense, the long goodbye

00:19:27.720 --> 00:19:29.940
I think is difficult

00:19:29.940 --> 00:19:33.180
because role reversal is difficult.

00:19:33.180 --> 00:19:36.780
And I think I learned that enough to say,

00:19:36.780 --> 00:19:38.700
look, I love you.

00:19:39.810 --> 00:19:42.780
I might think I have a
lot you can learn from me.

00:19:42.780 --> 00:19:45.420
And I said to him, but
don't listen to old CEOs.

00:19:45.420 --> 00:19:47.460
Former CEOs or former CEOs.

00:19:47.460 --> 00:19:49.140
You're gonna know what to do

00:19:49.140 --> 00:19:51.690
and anything you don't know,
you're gonna figure out.

00:19:53.370 --> 00:19:54.990
- What was it about Satya?

00:19:54.990 --> 00:19:57.690
Satya was not beholden to the past.

00:19:57.690 --> 00:20:01.020
He was not beholden to making
sure that Office help Windows.

00:20:01.020 --> 00:20:03.420
And so he was able to make
decisions, I think in a way

00:20:03.420 --> 00:20:05.730
that was a little bit freeing.

00:20:05.730 --> 00:20:08.730
Steve famously got upset
when employees had iPhones.

00:20:08.730 --> 00:20:10.140
Satya wanted everybody

00:20:10.140 --> 00:20:13.470
to experience everyone else's
products to know about them.

00:20:14.430 --> 00:20:15.600
I remember talking to someone,

00:20:15.600 --> 00:20:18.360
an executive from another
company, had been at a conference

00:20:18.360 --> 00:20:21.390
with Satya and every single
business leader in the room kept

00:20:21.390 --> 00:20:24.210
pulling out their Blackberry,
checking their email.

00:20:24.210 --> 00:20:27.120
Satya didn't look at it the
whole day, he just listened.

00:20:27.120 --> 00:20:28.560
- Brett, I mean, how confident are you

00:20:28.560 --> 00:20:31.243
that Nadella can bring this company

00:20:31.243 --> 00:20:32.910
back from where it's been

00:20:32.910 --> 00:20:36.960
and sort of restore Microsoft to greatness

00:20:36.960 --> 00:20:39.150
and win in the places where it can?

00:20:39.150 --> 00:20:40.200
- There's not a tech leader

00:20:40.200 --> 00:20:41.730
who doesn't respect Satya Nadella.

00:20:41.730 --> 00:20:45.180
He's really taken a, an extremely
complex and large company

00:20:45.180 --> 00:20:47.890
and genuinely changed
its culture and strategy

00:20:47.890 --> 00:20:50.223
- With Satya, you know, his first reaction

00:20:50.223 --> 00:20:52.900
when the succession process was

00:20:52.900 --> 00:20:56.350
announced was not to
throw his hat in the ring.

00:20:56.350 --> 00:20:58.900
I mean, he literally said,
I don't think you need me.

00:20:58.900 --> 00:21:01.690
- Wow. - And then a couple
months later he said, well,

00:21:01.690 --> 00:21:03.070
I think maybe you need me.

00:21:05.320 --> 00:21:08.830
- This company's had three
CEOs, they're all right here.

00:21:08.830 --> 00:21:09.830
This is all,

00:21:11.980 --> 00:21:14.290
- Not everybody knew him as well.

00:21:14.290 --> 00:21:16.750
He had only been running
the cloud business

00:21:16.750 --> 00:21:18.430
for a little less than three years.

00:21:18.430 --> 00:21:19.570
If it had been two years later,

00:21:19.570 --> 00:21:20.680
I think it would've been obvious.

00:21:20.680 --> 00:21:23.020
So it was a bet.

00:21:23.020 --> 00:21:25.780
- You are credited with
leading Microsoft's comeback

00:21:25.780 --> 00:21:29.050
and you came in as kind of a wartime CEO.

00:21:29.050 --> 00:21:31.990
Is it peace time now or is it still war?

00:21:31.990 --> 00:21:34.605
- I mean, those metaphors
are interesting to me.

00:21:34.605 --> 00:21:37.510
I, I feel like the
Microsoft I grew up in was

00:21:37.510 --> 00:21:41.500
that there was no such thing
as, oh wow, we won anything.

00:21:41.500 --> 00:21:43.420
So at least the core DNA

00:21:43.420 --> 00:21:48.340
and the core posture I've had
in throughout my 32 years at

00:21:48.340 --> 00:21:51.640
Microsoft is we better
get our act together

00:21:51.640 --> 00:21:54.370
to make sure we are
learning fast enough about

00:21:54.370 --> 00:21:55.960
what the next big thing is.

00:21:55.960 --> 00:21:59.740
It's all about, hey, are we
being relevant in the future?

00:21:59.740 --> 00:22:01.750
That's the only way to survive.

00:22:01.750 --> 00:22:04.060
- When Satya Nadella
took the reins in 2014,

00:22:04.060 --> 00:22:06.490
he challenged the windows
obsessed hierarchy

00:22:06.490 --> 00:22:09.250
and reoriented Microsoft
around the cloud and AI.

00:22:10.330 --> 00:22:13.870
It worked and the stock talked
to the delight of Ballmer,

00:22:13.870 --> 00:22:16.150
Microsoft's largest shareholder.

00:22:16.150 --> 00:22:19.090
- Everything's three times
as big, revenue's three times

00:22:19.090 --> 00:22:21.070
as big profit is three oh market caps

00:22:21.070 --> 00:22:22.540
more than three times as big.

00:22:22.540 --> 00:22:25.750
All good by me. So every, you
know, everything is scaled

00:22:25.750 --> 00:22:28.540
so much it's, it's amazing.

00:22:28.540 --> 00:22:30.700
- Microsoft surged back
to Wall Street Glory

00:22:30.700 --> 00:22:32.830
with the magnificent seven shorthand

00:22:32.830 --> 00:22:34.270
for high performing tech stocks

00:22:34.270 --> 00:22:37.090
with market caps bigger
than some countries.

00:22:37.090 --> 00:22:39.280
The hardest lesson you've learned as CEO?

00:22:39.280 --> 00:22:43.690
- I think the hardest one is to be able

00:22:43.690 --> 00:22:47.230
to really live that, right?

00:22:47.230 --> 00:22:49.930
To deliver the present and

00:22:49.930 --> 00:22:51.520
then prepare for the future.

00:22:51.520 --> 00:22:53.860
That ability, like as a CEO,
what is it that you have

00:22:53.860 --> 00:22:55.000
to do each quarter?

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:57.370
You have to create magic, right?

00:22:57.370 --> 00:22:59.470
That's kind of what
every 90 days the market

00:22:59.470 --> 00:23:00.880
expects you to create magic.

00:23:00.880 --> 00:23:03.610
And that's kind of the reality
of the world we live in.

00:23:03.610 --> 00:23:06.310
While at the same time building
a long-term institution

00:23:06.310 --> 00:23:09.220
and the accountability that
goes with it, being able to sort

00:23:09.220 --> 00:23:11.550
of understand what it takes to have

00:23:11.550 --> 00:23:14.890
that ultimate accountability
to both deliver today

00:23:14.890 --> 00:23:16.270
and for tomorrow

00:23:16.270 --> 00:23:18.160
and to be able to get that balance right.

00:23:18.160 --> 00:23:21.190
- It's a much more complex job
today I have to say I'm in,

00:23:21.190 --> 00:23:25.930
you know, great admiration for
how zen he is at, you know,

00:23:25.930 --> 00:23:28.000
picking the things he's gonna focus on

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:31.510
and all the, you know, choices.

00:23:31.510 --> 00:23:34.240
He's very good about
drawing both Steve and I in.

00:23:34.240 --> 00:23:38.980
So whatever expertise we have,
he gets the benefit of that,

00:23:38.980 --> 00:23:40.570
you know, so I think he's kind of a model.

00:23:40.570 --> 00:23:42.760
He wasn't there in the early days

00:23:42.760 --> 00:23:46.910
and yet, you know, of all the
tech companies, I think he's,

00:23:46.910 --> 00:23:48.680
he's been the best at carrying forward.

00:23:48.680 --> 00:23:52.400
Even the original spirit of
what made Microsoft special.

00:23:53.390 --> 00:23:56.090
- Nadella's legacy includes big
investments in acquisitions

00:23:56.090 --> 00:23:59.390
from LinkedIn, GitHub,
Activision Blizzard to

00:23:59.390 --> 00:24:01.580
what some have called
the deal of the decade,

00:24:01.580 --> 00:24:04.271
a $13 billion bet on OpenAI.

00:24:04.271 --> 00:24:05.990
Microsoft's biggest hit?

00:24:05.990 --> 00:24:07.970
- Windows
- Biggest Miss?

00:24:07.970 --> 00:24:08.970
- Clippy.

00:24:10.145 --> 00:24:11.960
It was just ahead of its time.

00:24:11.960 --> 00:24:14.510
It was just ahead of its
time. It's back again.

00:24:14.510 --> 00:24:15.950
- Biggest surprise.

00:24:15.950 --> 00:24:20.930
- The biggest surprise was maybe,

00:24:20.930 --> 00:24:24.172
maybe this OpenAI ChatGPT.

00:24:24.172 --> 00:24:26.690
Having a chat interface become a hit

00:24:26.690 --> 00:24:28.460
was a real surprise.

00:24:28.460 --> 00:24:30.890
- The concept of a chat bot isn't new.

00:24:30.890 --> 00:24:33.080
They tried before with Clippy, Cortana

00:24:33.080 --> 00:24:35.930
and Tay, the bot that had
to be shut down 16 hours

00:24:35.930 --> 00:24:36.775
after launch.

00:24:36.775 --> 00:24:39.758
- Soon, Tay was ranting about Hitler.

00:24:39.758 --> 00:24:42.230
But ChatGPT was a massive success

00:24:42.230 --> 00:24:46.190
giving Microsoft a surprise
jump in the AI race.

00:24:46.190 --> 00:24:50.240
The deal with OpenAI, was it
smart, lucky, or a quick fix?

00:24:50.240 --> 00:24:52.430
- It's hard to argue
anything other than smart.

00:24:52.430 --> 00:24:55.610
The original deal back in, you know, 2019,

00:24:55.610 --> 00:24:57.140
nobody really knew if it was

00:24:57.140 --> 00:24:58.518
gonna work out the way they said, right?

00:24:58.518 --> 00:25:00.440
And Bill Gates opposed

00:25:00.440 --> 00:25:02.720
that deal on technological grounds

00:25:02.720 --> 00:25:05.690
because Bill thought that
the way that the technology

00:25:05.690 --> 00:25:08.750
of the AI market would play out
was gonna be a different way

00:25:08.750 --> 00:25:09.920
and that what Sam

00:25:09.920 --> 00:25:12.050
and company wanted to do wasn't
gonna be how it would work.

00:25:12.050 --> 00:25:14.690
Lucky that they picked
the right horse perhaps.

00:25:14.690 --> 00:25:18.140
- The OpenAI Microsoft
partnership delivered a hit.

00:25:18.140 --> 00:25:20.120
But there've been some
bumps along the way.

00:25:21.110 --> 00:25:24.980
- It is full mutiny within
the world's most important

00:25:24.980 --> 00:25:26.270
AI company

00:25:26.270 --> 00:25:28.520
- Who's gonna be CEO of OpenAI tomorrow?

00:25:28.520 --> 00:25:29.520
- You tell me.

00:25:31.100 --> 00:25:33.680
- I will leave it to OpenAI and its board.

00:25:33.680 --> 00:25:35.390
- What's Satya like in a crisis?

00:25:35.390 --> 00:25:37.610
Satya, to me that
weekend, was like a duck.

00:25:37.610 --> 00:25:39.830
He was completely calm above the water

00:25:39.830 --> 00:25:42.860
and underneath the water
he was paddling furiously.

00:25:42.860 --> 00:25:44.930
You pointed out to me that
quote that about, you know,

00:25:44.930 --> 00:25:47.030
Microsoft being above them,
below them, around them

00:25:47.030 --> 00:25:48.350
and you know, which sounds kind

00:25:48.350 --> 00:25:49.880
of scary, but really it's true.

00:25:49.880 --> 00:25:51.950
The contract that Microsoft had struck

00:25:51.950 --> 00:25:53.780
and with OpenAI really gave them access

00:25:53.780 --> 00:25:56.180
to everything no matter what happened.

00:25:56.180 --> 00:25:58.820
And at the same time, things are starting

00:25:58.820 --> 00:26:00.560
to change on the basis of that

00:26:00.560 --> 00:26:02.570
- Microsoft is building its own models.

00:26:02.570 --> 00:26:04.520
OpenAI is making other friends

00:26:04.520 --> 00:26:06.800
and your partnership ends in 2030.

00:26:06.800 --> 00:26:08.360
Are you trying to tell the kids

00:26:08.360 --> 00:26:11.600
that maybe this marriage isn't forever?

00:26:11.600 --> 00:26:15.110
- This is another thing I
learned in the last 50 years is,

00:26:15.110 --> 00:26:16.820
you know, you approach all partnerships

00:26:16.820 --> 00:26:18.140
and create long-term stable

00:26:18.140 --> 00:26:19.610
partnerships which are win-win, right?

00:26:19.610 --> 00:26:22.190
So I hope that for
decades to come, Microsoft

00:26:22.190 --> 00:26:25.100
and OpenAI will be partnered
in variety of different ways.

00:26:25.100 --> 00:26:27.320
Will they have other partners? Absolutely.

00:26:27.320 --> 00:26:29.360
Will we have other partners? Absolutely.

00:26:29.360 --> 00:26:31.040
- But the relationship is changing, right?

00:26:31.040 --> 00:26:33.380
Like how is it changing and
what happens when that deal is?

00:26:33.380 --> 00:26:34.760
- I think that any company

00:26:34.760 --> 00:26:37.460
that has gone from being
a research lab to one

00:26:37.460 --> 00:26:40.280
of the most successful
product companies of this age,

00:26:40.280 --> 00:26:42.350
obviously things have to change for them

00:26:42.350 --> 00:26:45.120
and for us in the context
of the partnership, right?

00:26:45.120 --> 00:26:47.520
We have IP rights, we are thrilled about

00:26:47.520 --> 00:26:51.030
that access we have, we are
infrastructure providers,

00:26:51.030 --> 00:26:53.010
they're the biggest customers of ours.

00:26:53.010 --> 00:26:56.550
And so to us, having
that multifaceted sort

00:26:56.550 --> 00:26:59.130
of partnership is what
we are really focused on.

00:26:59.130 --> 00:27:01.620
And so why would any one
of us want to go upset that

00:27:02.460 --> 00:27:04.200
- Still, business is business.

00:27:04.200 --> 00:27:06.660
And it seems like there's
always a new twist on tap in

00:27:06.660 --> 00:27:09.930
that relentless pursuit
of relevance as we saw

00:27:09.930 --> 00:27:11.670
with search in your
competition with Google,

00:27:11.670 --> 00:27:13.710
sometimes you just can't fight the verb.

00:27:13.710 --> 00:27:17.550
It's habit-forming and ChatGPT
is the verb right now.

00:27:17.550 --> 00:27:19.590
So how much do you worry

00:27:19.590 --> 00:27:22.680
that Microsoft loses the mind share game

00:27:22.680 --> 00:27:24.654
- Every day that ChatGPT succeeds

00:27:24.654 --> 00:27:26.562
is a fantastic day for Microsoft,

00:27:26.562 --> 00:27:28.012
Right, every time you search on ChatGPT,

00:27:28.012 --> 00:27:29.838
Microsoft makes money, right?

00:27:29.838 --> 00:27:33.540
Yeah. In some sense it does
prove the point that, you know,

00:27:33.540 --> 00:27:35.010
markets can evolve

00:27:35.010 --> 00:27:37.350
and new hit products
can be created from

00:27:37.350 --> 00:27:38.970
anywhere and what have you.

00:27:38.970 --> 00:27:41.130
- How will the AI wars play out?

00:27:41.130 --> 00:27:43.020
Like does it feel
different than the mobile

00:27:43.020 --> 00:27:44.700
or the browser wars?

00:27:44.700 --> 00:27:46.020
Like who wins?

00:27:46.020 --> 00:27:48.060
- Well, we don't know.

00:27:48.060 --> 00:27:51.270
We know that the level of investment

00:27:51.270 --> 00:27:54.810
by the leading companies
is pretty mind blowing.

00:27:54.810 --> 00:27:58.800
You know, Google's a great
company, Microsoft, OpenAI.

00:27:58.800 --> 00:28:02.160
We're out there, you
know, every day, you know,

00:28:02.160 --> 00:28:04.050
making Copilot better.

00:28:04.050 --> 00:28:06.900
- You obviously have a
booming enterprise business.

00:28:06.900 --> 00:28:09.510
When you look at what Google
is doing and Apple and Meta

00:28:09.510 --> 00:28:12.420
and Amazon, how important is it to you

00:28:12.420 --> 00:28:16.470
to win in consumer AI
and how do you do that?

00:28:16.470 --> 00:28:18.360
- To me, I want us to
play to our strength.

00:28:18.360 --> 00:28:19.980
Like if I look at even what we are doing

00:28:19.980 --> 00:28:21.450
with copilot, right?

00:28:21.450 --> 00:28:23.100
How do we build a Copilot

00:28:23.100 --> 00:28:26.790
that's the new browser
effectively in this intelligence

00:28:26.790 --> 00:28:31.500
era that has a unique
characteristic of that is Microsoft.

00:28:31.500 --> 00:28:34.260
Whether it's helping you
with your travel planning

00:28:34.260 --> 00:28:37.560
or whether it's shopping
or with your homework,

00:28:37.560 --> 00:28:40.740
but do it in a way that
it uniquely telegraphs

00:28:40.740 --> 00:28:43.320
what I think Microsoft's
signature would be in it.

00:28:43.320 --> 00:28:46.110
In what is going to be
a new way to litigate

00:28:46.110 --> 00:28:47.400
what is the consumer market

00:28:49.530 --> 00:28:53.040
- Outside of video games, Xbox, Satya

00:28:53.040 --> 00:28:55.380
and team have just not
figured out consumer

00:28:55.380 --> 00:28:58.710
and it's becoming
potentially more of an issue

00:28:58.710 --> 00:29:02.580
because our generation grew
up in Microsoft products.

00:29:02.580 --> 00:29:05.400
The generation that's
in school now does not.

00:29:05.400 --> 00:29:08.610
They live in Google,
they have Apple devices.

00:29:08.610 --> 00:29:10.410
You have a generation growing up

00:29:10.410 --> 00:29:13.620
and the question for Microsoft
is what is their entree

00:29:13.620 --> 00:29:16.860
to Microsoft products if they're
not growing up with them?

00:29:16.860 --> 00:29:19.380
- Microsoft got a headstart
with exclusive access

00:29:19.380 --> 00:29:22.110
to open AI's models,
but the boardroom drama

00:29:22.110 --> 00:29:24.120
and Big Tech competition pushed Nadella

00:29:24.120 --> 00:29:25.350
to innovate from within.

00:29:26.247 --> 00:29:27.080
- Hello.

00:29:27.080 --> 00:29:29.496
- Hey, good to see you.
- Great to see you.

00:29:29.496 --> 00:29:32.640
Mustafa Suleyman is head of
Microsoft's consumer AI team

00:29:32.640 --> 00:29:35.130
who came in-house in a buzzy acquihire.

00:29:35.130 --> 00:29:38.760
Suleyman's job is to make
Microsoft's own chatbot, Copilot,

00:29:38.760 --> 00:29:42.130
as essential as Excel or
Windows in a big bet on the next

00:29:42.130 --> 00:29:43.270
era of computing.

00:29:43.270 --> 00:29:45.580
- Everything is about to shuffle.

00:29:45.580 --> 00:29:48.280
Whether it's search or the browser or apps

00:29:48.280 --> 00:29:50.230
or the operating system.

00:29:50.230 --> 00:29:52.900
These models are just
completely different to any one

00:29:52.900 --> 00:29:55.360
of those last generations of software.

00:29:55.360 --> 00:29:56.451
- So right now you feel like

00:29:56.451 --> 00:29:58.900
you have a once-in-a-decade opportunity.

00:29:58.900 --> 00:30:00.580
- I really do. I think these next couple

00:30:00.580 --> 00:30:03.160
of years are gonna be a defining moment.

00:30:03.160 --> 00:30:05.800
We're gonna look back and
be like, this was the era

00:30:05.800 --> 00:30:09.190
of real agents, you
know, forming a lasting,

00:30:09.190 --> 00:30:12.490
meaningful relationship
with an AI companion

00:30:12.490 --> 00:30:14.380
that becomes the primary way

00:30:14.380 --> 00:30:16.150
that you do computing in the world.

00:30:16.990 --> 00:30:18.460
- He's trying to create a seamless

00:30:18.460 --> 00:30:21.100
and futuristic consumer AI experience,

00:30:21.100 --> 00:30:23.260
a new mission for Microsoft.

00:30:23.260 --> 00:30:26.530
- The number one priority
for us is that we have

00:30:26.530 --> 00:30:31.240
to produce beautiful,
elegant, consumer products

00:30:31.240 --> 00:30:34.270
that regular young people love, right?

00:30:34.270 --> 00:30:37.570
And that is not the way
that young people think

00:30:37.570 --> 00:30:39.460
of Microsoft's products today.

00:30:39.460 --> 00:30:41.560
And that's a very big
shift in our thinking.

00:30:41.560 --> 00:30:44.200
- Microsoft's product suite
still, I think has a lot

00:30:44.200 --> 00:30:47.290
of challenges and in
many ways can feel dated

00:30:50.020 --> 00:30:52.780
- Like Excel, you're making me cry.

00:30:52.780 --> 00:30:55.462
When are we banning Microsoft Outlook?

00:30:55.462 --> 00:30:58.960
I spent two hours today
trying to open an email.

00:30:58.960 --> 00:31:00.340
You have one job.

00:31:00.340 --> 00:31:05.020
How do you make it smarter, but
still simple and delightful?

00:31:05.020 --> 00:31:06.670
- So you clearly want it

00:31:06.670 --> 00:31:09.103
to reason over your past data,

00:31:09.103 --> 00:31:11.530
use your personal information,

00:31:11.530 --> 00:31:13.750
and then get really good at taking actions

00:31:13.750 --> 00:31:17.260
inside the browser, searching
for things on your behalf.

00:31:17.260 --> 00:31:19.030
And that's just an iterative process

00:31:19.030 --> 00:31:20.470
that, you know, is gonna take many,

00:31:20.470 --> 00:31:22.355
many quarters to come to pass.

00:31:22.355 --> 00:31:24.550
- What do you think your approach,

00:31:24.550 --> 00:31:27.520
your secret is going to be?

00:31:27.520 --> 00:31:29.530
- I think humor is gonna be central.

00:31:29.530 --> 00:31:31.960
It's gotta have a sense of itself,

00:31:31.960 --> 00:31:33.760
a little bit of character.

00:31:33.760 --> 00:31:37.000
It needs to remember
you and know who you are

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:39.220
and that range of personalization,

00:31:39.220 --> 00:31:41.260
that's gonna be a key differentiator.

00:31:41.260 --> 00:31:43.570
- Alright, we're gonna try
out some different voices

00:31:43.570 --> 00:31:46.930
- Looking for answers
or a new perspective?

00:31:46.930 --> 00:31:49.450
- Let's chat and figure it out together.

00:31:49.450 --> 00:31:50.283
- Whoa!

00:31:50.283 --> 00:31:52.737
- I want to hear your big ideas.

00:31:52.737 --> 00:31:53.570
- Ooh

00:31:53.570 --> 00:31:56.528
- I can write stories, brainstorm ideas,

00:31:56.528 --> 00:31:59.920
and I can sound like this if you choose.

00:31:59.920 --> 00:32:01.780
- That sounds a lot like Mustafa to me.

00:32:01.780 --> 00:32:02.613
- Hey Copilot.

00:32:02.613 --> 00:32:04.240
- Does it sound like Mustafa to you?

00:32:04.240 --> 00:32:06.280
So I have a big tech conference coming up

00:32:06.280 --> 00:32:07.870
and I'm trying to think
of people we should

00:32:07.870 --> 00:32:09.670
invite to interview.

00:32:09.670 --> 00:32:10.900
Do you have any ideas?

00:32:12.730 --> 00:32:15.130
- You could consider
inviting Satya Nadella

00:32:15.130 --> 00:32:17.500
for insights on AI and cloud?

00:32:17.500 --> 00:32:20.650
Cheryl Sandberg for social
media and leadership.

00:32:20.650 --> 00:32:22.900
- I find it interesting that
Satya's your first choice.

00:32:22.900 --> 00:32:24.116
Is that because he's your boss?

00:32:25.475 --> 00:32:26.308
Not at all.

00:32:27.160 --> 00:32:28.270
Are we all just gonna be talking to our

00:32:28.270 --> 00:32:30.370
computers and our phones?
Is that the next wave?

00:32:30.370 --> 00:32:33.340
- I think the voice is gonna
be one of the next platforms.

00:32:33.340 --> 00:32:36.040
It's not gonna replace all
the previous platforms.

00:32:36.040 --> 00:32:37.120
It's like a fork.

00:32:37.120 --> 00:32:38.844
It enables a completely different way

00:32:38.844 --> 00:32:40.850
of talking to your computer.

00:32:40.850 --> 00:32:42.440
- No matter which chatbot wins,

00:32:42.440 --> 00:32:44.300
demand is expected to grow.

00:32:44.300 --> 00:32:47.060
Sending Big Tech on a
massive spending spree.

00:32:47.060 --> 00:32:50.990
- Microsoft's putting out
$80 billion of investment.

00:32:50.990 --> 00:32:53.630
You know, clearly that's
the sense that, wow,

00:32:53.630 --> 00:32:55.610
we have something that
customers are gonna want.

00:32:55.610 --> 00:32:57.440
We're willing to invest at a level

00:32:57.440 --> 00:32:59.270
that's completely unheard of.

00:32:59.270 --> 00:33:02.540
I mean that's, it's a
pretty mind blowing number.

00:33:02.540 --> 00:33:04.310
- We're in this new computing era.

00:33:04.310 --> 00:33:05.480
Tech giants including you,

00:33:05.480 --> 00:33:07.670
are building these AI data centers.

00:33:07.670 --> 00:33:09.770
Do you have any concerns about the size

00:33:09.770 --> 00:33:11.420
and scale of this bet?

00:33:11.420 --> 00:33:14.720
Like are we building the
future the right way?

00:33:14.720 --> 00:33:17.420
- I think the the scale
is pretty stunning,

00:33:17.420 --> 00:33:19.940
but the real test here, Emily, is

00:33:19.940 --> 00:33:21.470
what happens in the real economy?

00:33:21.470 --> 00:33:25.700
The real test is not some
benchmark or what have you of AI

00:33:25.700 --> 00:33:27.350
It's one simple fact,

00:33:27.350 --> 00:33:29.870
which is when we start
seeing higher growth rates

00:33:29.870 --> 00:33:32.330
around the world and the
benefits of that growth rate,

00:33:32.330 --> 00:33:36.230
by the way, being much more
broader cross-sectorally

00:33:36.230 --> 00:33:37.820
and by economic strata,

00:33:37.820 --> 00:33:39.770
then I think we would've
achieved something.

00:33:39.770 --> 00:33:41.870
- The emergence of deep seek from China.

00:33:41.870 --> 00:33:44.630
You told your team to quickly
integrate it into Azure.

00:33:44.630 --> 00:33:46.610
Why don't you think it's a risk and

00:33:46.610 --> 00:33:49.100
and what do you think of
China's role in this fight?

00:33:49.100 --> 00:33:52.940
- The thing that I think about
is there'll always be open

00:33:52.940 --> 00:33:54.500
source and if anything,

00:33:54.500 --> 00:33:56.930
what DeepSeek is proven
is open source can

00:33:56.930 --> 00:33:58.130
come from any place.

00:33:58.130 --> 00:34:00.020
In this case it happens
to come from China.

00:34:00.020 --> 00:34:02.090
The next model may come
from some other country,

00:34:02.090 --> 00:34:04.700
it may come from the
lab in the United States.

00:34:04.700 --> 00:34:07.370
It doesn't matter. In this
industry, we better sort

00:34:07.370 --> 00:34:10.910
of really face up to the
fact that this is the rate

00:34:10.910 --> 00:34:13.310
of diffusion that's faster
than anything before

00:34:13.310 --> 00:34:14.660
and it's worldwide.

00:34:20.150 --> 00:34:22.070
- There's a version of
AI that's a security

00:34:22.070 --> 00:34:23.660
and privacy nightmare.

00:34:23.660 --> 00:34:25.040
How do you think about it?

00:34:25.040 --> 00:34:27.770
- Well, I think that it's
just an imperative for us

00:34:27.770 --> 00:34:28.940
to protect security

00:34:28.940 --> 00:34:32.090
and privacy in every aspect of technology.

00:34:32.090 --> 00:34:34.910
Whether we're talking
about AI or social media

00:34:34.910 --> 00:34:37.730
or the content we created work.

00:34:37.730 --> 00:34:42.560
The aspect of AI that is most
interesting is that it is sort

00:34:42.560 --> 00:34:45.470
of the ultimate tool
and the ultimate weapon.

00:34:51.140 --> 00:34:52.580
- So the question I wanted to address

00:34:52.580 --> 00:34:54.560
today is really simple.

00:34:54.560 --> 00:34:56.120
What does all this mean?

00:34:56.120 --> 00:34:57.732
- Mustafa, shame on you.

00:34:57.732 --> 00:35:00.497
You say you, you claim that
you care about using AI

00:35:00.497 --> 00:35:02.180
for good, but Microsoft sells

00:35:02.180 --> 00:35:04.915
AI weapons to the Israeli
military. You are -

00:35:04.915 --> 00:35:07.160
- I hear your protest. Thank you.

00:35:07.160 --> 00:35:08.177
- Shame on you.

00:35:09.460 --> 00:35:11.210
- Microsoft is a war puppeteer.

00:35:11.210 --> 00:35:13.734
Microsoft is a war puppeteer!

00:35:13.734 --> 00:35:14.959
Not everyone is along

00:35:14.959 --> 00:35:17.990
for the tech industry's
ride to the AI promise land.

00:35:17.990 --> 00:35:19.010
There are consequences

00:35:19.010 --> 00:35:20.030
and challenges ahead

00:35:20.030 --> 00:35:22.370
as this new underlying technology embeds

00:35:22.370 --> 00:35:24.170
itself into everything.

00:35:24.170 --> 00:35:26.360
Do you think we're gonna
really look back on this march

00:35:26.360 --> 00:35:29.960
of progress as positive?

00:35:29.960 --> 00:35:32.120
You know, I've heard Bill talk
about how he never thought

00:35:32.120 --> 00:35:33.170
that tech could be negative

00:35:33.170 --> 00:35:35.600
until the the era of social networking.

00:35:35.600 --> 00:35:38.340
I guess I wonder if this
sort relentless march

00:35:38.340 --> 00:35:41.310
of progress could in the
future mean fewer jobs,

00:35:41.310 --> 00:35:46.310
fewer opportunities, less
meaning in our lives.

00:35:46.530 --> 00:35:48.120
- I think it's super important

00:35:48.120 --> 00:35:50.370
to acknowledge the uncertainty

00:35:50.370 --> 00:35:53.280
around what's gonna unfold
over the next 10 or 20 years.

00:35:54.330 --> 00:35:58.860
Anyone who is confident is probably wrong.

00:35:58.860 --> 00:36:02.580
And so that means that we
have to be alive to the fact

00:36:02.580 --> 00:36:05.670
that this really is different
to other types of technology.

00:36:05.670 --> 00:36:10.020
It is not just a simple tool,
it's dynamic, it's emergent,

00:36:10.020 --> 00:36:12.120
it adapts to you on the fly.

00:36:12.120 --> 00:36:13.710
And that means there could be all kinds

00:36:13.710 --> 00:36:16.890
of third degree effects that
are quite hard to predict.

00:36:16.890 --> 00:36:18.600
- You've said that the age

00:36:18.600 --> 00:36:22.320
of complete human dominance
will be over in 10 years.

00:36:22.320 --> 00:36:24.480
What does that really mean for us?

00:36:24.480 --> 00:36:26.940
- What it means goes beyond, you know,

00:36:26.940 --> 00:36:29.280
which company actually delivers that

00:36:29.280 --> 00:36:30.576
or what their stock price is.

00:36:30.576 --> 00:36:34.680
It's a much more profound thing
than just like the browser

00:36:34.680 --> 00:36:37.560
wars were, I mean it didn't
matter to people really

00:36:37.560 --> 00:36:39.503
who won the browser wars.

00:36:39.503 --> 00:36:42.840
Here, the capacity,

00:36:42.840 --> 00:36:47.190
the intelligence will give
humans a lot of choices.

00:36:47.190 --> 00:36:49.650
- It's a complicated picture
for the software giant.

00:36:49.650 --> 00:36:51.630
Its mission is the future of work,

00:36:51.630 --> 00:36:53.160
but it's investing in technology

00:36:53.160 --> 00:36:55.980
that's reshaping the
future of opportunity.

00:36:55.980 --> 00:36:57.960
AI powered coding assistance are changing

00:36:57.960 --> 00:37:01.050
how software gets built,
automating tasks normally handled

00:37:01.050 --> 00:37:02.580
by junior developers.

00:37:02.580 --> 00:37:05.010
That's become a bragging
point at the very top.

00:37:05.010 --> 00:37:07.710
- And so I would say maybe
20, 30% of the code that is

00:37:07.710 --> 00:37:09.900
inside of our reposts today in some

00:37:09.900 --> 00:37:12.510
of our projects are probably all written

00:37:12.510 --> 00:37:14.430
by software. What about you guys?

00:37:14.430 --> 00:37:16.980
- I don't know, maybe half
the development is gonna be

00:37:16.980 --> 00:37:18.540
- Done by AI.

00:37:18.540 --> 00:37:22.500
- Is AI gonna make engineers obsolete?

00:37:22.500 --> 00:37:27.420
- AI is gonna vastly change
the way software gets built.

00:37:27.420 --> 00:37:30.330
It will, and yet there's
still gonna be people who have

00:37:30.330 --> 00:37:33.960
to figure out what the world needs,

00:37:33.960 --> 00:37:35.610
how to give it to 'em.

00:37:35.610 --> 00:37:38.910
Will all of the code crunching activities

00:37:38.910 --> 00:37:41.220
of yesterday be around tomorrow?

00:37:41.220 --> 00:37:44.760
No. A lot of those will go
away. But I, I'm an optimist.

00:37:44.760 --> 00:37:47.880
People say, oh, you know, are
you gonna put people out of,

00:37:47.880 --> 00:37:49.740
and this happened every time.

00:37:49.740 --> 00:37:52.170
- Yeah. - You know, will
this cause a loss of jobs?

00:37:52.170 --> 00:37:53.850
Will that cause a lot of jobs?

00:37:53.850 --> 00:37:56.880
You know what I'd say?
Somehow the world's always

00:37:56.880 --> 00:37:58.610
created new jobs.

00:37:58.610 --> 00:38:01.170
It can be hard. The
dislocation people say,

00:38:01.170 --> 00:38:02.490
oh shoot, it's my skills,

00:38:02.490 --> 00:38:04.080
it became obsolete.

00:38:04.080 --> 00:38:07.710
But there will be new
important skills people need.

00:38:07.710 --> 00:38:09.360
- What's gonna be the it job

00:38:09.360 --> 00:38:12.750
of the future if it was a
software programmer in your era?

00:38:12.750 --> 00:38:15.240
- Well, I'm not sure there's any it job.

00:38:15.240 --> 00:38:17.400
If you love math and software, great.

00:38:17.400 --> 00:38:18.750
Go be a software programmer.

00:38:18.750 --> 00:38:21.690
But that was, you know, the
percentage of the labor market

00:38:21.690 --> 00:38:25.740
that was, you know, nerdy
people like me, you know,

00:38:25.740 --> 00:38:29.100
where you'd be writing code,
you know, is pretty modest.

00:38:29.100 --> 00:38:32.220
All of that, those
capabilities where you bring it

00:38:32.220 --> 00:38:35.470
as a human, I think will
still be fairly important.

00:38:35.470 --> 00:38:37.510
But it is a, a period

00:38:37.510 --> 00:38:41.680
where answering these
questions is probably harder

00:38:41.680 --> 00:38:43.270
than at any time in history.

00:38:44.200 --> 00:38:47.320
- I think it takes like unique
human arrogance to believe

00:38:47.320 --> 00:38:50.590
that AI cannot supersede humans.

00:38:50.590 --> 00:38:52.120
- But what about that scares you?

00:38:53.260 --> 00:38:55.780
- So many things, right?
Like this is like, you know,

00:38:55.780 --> 00:38:57.220
what does it mean to build something

00:38:57.220 --> 00:38:59.463
that is more capable than
ourselves?

00:38:59.463 --> 00:39:01.556
There are folks out there
including Sam Altman

00:39:01.556 --> 00:39:04.120
and OpenAI who believe super intelligent,

00:39:04.120 --> 00:39:06.040
super powerful AI's right

00:39:06.040 --> 00:39:08.200
around the corner. What's your bet?

00:39:08.200 --> 00:39:10.360
- I think that we are definitely on a path

00:39:10.360 --> 00:39:12.370
to have more powerful systems pretty soon

00:39:12.370 --> 00:39:15.220
- Is AGI being built on
Microsoft's campus right now?

00:39:15.220 --> 00:39:16.990
Like can we go find it?

00:39:16.990 --> 00:39:19.210
- No, you can't find it. It doesn't exist.

00:39:19.210 --> 00:39:20.320
- How confident are you

00:39:20.320 --> 00:39:23.350
that AI's promise will
outweigh the perils?

00:39:24.305 --> 00:39:25.960
- I'm, I'm not confident,

00:39:25.960 --> 00:39:29.230
but the, you know, that's,
that's what we need

00:39:29.230 --> 00:39:30.340
to get oriented around.

00:39:30.340 --> 00:39:32.650
That's why I was surprised AI
wasn't really an issue in the

00:39:32.650 --> 00:39:34.210
last election.

00:39:34.210 --> 00:39:36.310
It's definitely got to be shaped.

00:39:36.310 --> 00:39:39.130
- Hearing you say you're not
confident is kind of scary.

00:39:39.130 --> 00:39:43.000
- People should think
through how is AI going

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:45.460
to reshape our lives?

00:39:45.460 --> 00:39:50.200
It is, it is a profound change agent.

00:39:50.200 --> 00:39:53.260
And you know, I don't think
it should just be the people

00:39:53.260 --> 00:39:54.550
who know the technology

00:39:54.550 --> 00:39:57.730
because there's a lot of
choices about how it gets used.

00:39:57.730 --> 00:40:01.000
It will change learning, it
will change the job market.

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:02.890
And you know, I think we can shape

00:40:02.890 --> 00:40:04.270
that in a, in the right way.

00:40:04.270 --> 00:40:08.710
But it'll be, you know,
just like nuclear energy,

00:40:08.710 --> 00:40:09.760
nuclear weapons.

00:40:09.760 --> 00:40:12.580
It'll challenge us.

00:40:15.970 --> 00:40:19.510
- Thank you for your vision,
your leadership, your passion,

00:40:19.510 --> 00:40:22.720
and for building the
Microsoft that we know today.

00:40:22.720 --> 00:40:26.530
A company that has
truly changed the world.

00:40:26.530 --> 00:40:30.070
- What is Microsoft in 50
years? Like your best guess?

00:40:30.070 --> 00:40:33.580
- I mean a, a Petri dish with
a couple of cells connected

00:40:33.580 --> 00:40:36.850
to like an, an AI being
that controls everything.

00:40:36.850 --> 00:40:39.460
I don't know that we know
what it is in five years

00:40:39.460 --> 00:40:42.460
because we're talking about
the technological innovations

00:40:42.460 --> 00:40:45.160
here and how do they lead
with their own product

00:40:45.160 --> 00:40:47.470
and not just because they
picked the right model.

00:40:47.470 --> 00:40:50.140
Microsoft is preaching this gospel

00:40:50.140 --> 00:40:53.230
of AI changing everything
about the way we work.

00:40:53.230 --> 00:40:55.330
What Satya wants to see is for that

00:40:55.330 --> 00:40:58.000
to be proven out first at Microsoft.

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:00.940
- Microsoft changed the world.

00:41:00.940 --> 00:41:02.800
Well, Microsoft changed the world. Again,

00:41:02.800 --> 00:41:05.920
- I go back to that founding
moment when Bill said, you know

00:41:05.920 --> 00:41:08.320
what, the software industry
didn't exist and he

00:41:08.320 --> 00:41:11.320
and Paul sort of said, oh,
we should build software

00:41:11.320 --> 00:41:13.660
and hopefully we can monetize it

00:41:13.660 --> 00:41:15.760
and they will be an
industry. I mean, it's crazy.

00:41:15.760 --> 00:41:16.960
- Hopefully they will come.

00:41:16.960 --> 00:41:19.090
- Yeah. And, and it all happened.

00:41:19.090 --> 00:41:22.480
But the, the other thing about
it though was that core

00:41:22.480 --> 00:41:24.460
of, "Wow, we wanna build software so

00:41:24.460 --> 00:41:26.650
that others can create more software."

00:41:26.650 --> 00:41:29.710
That I think is what gives us relevance.

00:41:29.710 --> 00:41:31.810
I always say this,
longevity is not a goal,

00:41:31.810 --> 00:41:33.500
relevance is,

00:41:33.500 --> 00:41:37.310
and the framing of this company from 1975

00:41:37.310 --> 00:41:41.420
to 2025 has been the same,
which is can you do things

00:41:41.420 --> 00:41:44.180
that allow others to do more things?

00:41:44.180 --> 00:41:47.090
- If you could time travel to 2075,

00:41:47.090 --> 00:41:48.740
what advice would you give your successor?

00:41:48.740 --> 00:41:50.964
- The advice I got from Steve Ballmer

00:41:50.964 --> 00:41:52.480
when I took on the job is

00:41:52.480 --> 00:41:56.695
the advice that I think of all
the time, which is be bold.

00:41:56.695 --> 00:41:58.910
Because if you're not bold,
you're not gonna do anything.

00:41:58.910 --> 00:42:01.730
And be right because if you're not right,

00:42:01.730 --> 00:42:03.020
you won't amount to much.

00:42:03.020 --> 00:42:07.910
And so that ability to sort
of get past the status quo

00:42:07.910 --> 00:42:11.390
by really boldly thinking of
a future that doesn't exist,

00:42:11.390 --> 00:42:13.490
but then executing, right?

00:42:13.490 --> 00:42:16.130
At the end of the day,
business is about being able

00:42:16.130 --> 00:42:19.370
to earn the stripes one step at a time.

00:42:19.370 --> 00:42:21.380
And I think that's what
this company has exhibited.

00:42:21.380 --> 00:42:22.820
What has it has taught me all

00:42:22.820 --> 00:42:25.550
through my career at Microsoft,
which is you gotta dream

00:42:25.550 --> 00:42:27.440
and execute, dream and execute.

00:42:27.440 --> 00:42:29.180
And you know, we've not
gotten it always right.

00:42:29.180 --> 00:42:31.640
Both, either on the dream
side or on the execution side,

00:42:31.640 --> 00:42:34.040
but on the batting average is pretty good.

